title: Ancient Galaxy Cluster’s Extreme Heat Defies Universe Evolution Models
description: Astronomers discovered galaxy cluster SPT2349-56, existing 1.4 billion years post-Big Bang, with gas heated to over 100 million degrees Celsius—five times hotter than models predict. This anomaly, driven by supermassive black holes, suggests rapid cosmic structure formation, challenging standard theories of universe evolution.

title: 'How can all of this be happening?': Scientists spot massive group of ancient galaxies so hot they shouldn't exist
description: Skyler Ware is a freelance science journalist covering chemistry, biology, paleontology and Earth science. She was a 2023 AAAS Mass Media Science and Engineering Fellow at Science News.
